<b><center>Types of Relations</center></b><font size="--">
<FONT FACE="Arial"><UL><UL><B><LI>Reflexive Relations</LI>
<LI>Symmetric Relations</LI>
<LI>Anti Symmetric Relations</LI>
<LI>Transitive Relations</LI></UL></UL></b>

<B><P>Reflexive Relations</P>

</B><P>A relation R on a set A is <b>reflexive </b>if <b>aRa  <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#34;</FONT>
 a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 A. </b>  (<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#34;</FONT>
: read as ‘for all’)</P>

<B><P>Examples </B>:Consider the set A = {1, 2, 3, 4}</P>

<b><LI>R<SUB>1 </SUB>= {(1,1), (1,2), (2,3), (1,3), (4,4)}</b>

<UL>Here (3,3) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#207;</FONT>
 R<SUB>1</SUB> and (2,2) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#207;</FONT>
 R<SUB>1, 
</SUB>so R<SUB>1</SUB> is not reflexive.</P></UL>

<b><LI>R<SUB>2</SUB> = {(1,1), (1,2), (2,1), (2,2), (3,3), (4,4)}</b>

<UL>Here 1R<SUB>2</SUB>1, 2R<SUB>2</SUB>2, 3R<SUB>2</SUB>3, 4R<SUB>2</SUB>4, 

so R<SUB>2</SUB> is reflexive.</Br></UL>


<B><P>Symmetric Relations</P>
</B>
<P>A relation R on a set A is <b>symmetric</b> if whenever <b>aRb then bRa.

<br>i.e. If (a,b) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R then (b,a) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R.</b>

<B><P>Examples:</B> Consider the set A = {1, 2, 3, 4}</P>

<LI><b><P>R<SUB>1</SUB> = {(1,1), (1,2), (2,3), (1,3), (4,4)}</b>

<UL>Here (1,2) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R<SUB>1</SUB> but (2,1) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#207;</FONT>
 R<SUB>1</SUB>, so R<SUB>1</SUB> is not symmetric.</UL>

<LI><b>R<SUB>2</SUB> = {(1,1), (1,2), (2,1), (2,2), (3,3), (4,4)}</b>

<Br><ul>Here  (1,2) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R<SUB>2</SUB> and (2,1) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
  R<SUB>2</SUB>, so R<SUB>2</SUB> is symmetric.</UL>

<B><P>Anti Symmetric Relations</P>

</B><Br>A relation R on a set A is <B>Anti Symmetric</b> if whenever <B>aRb and bRa then a = b</B>, 
 
i.e. <B>If (a,b), (b,a) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R then a =b.</b>

<B><P>Example </P>
</B></b><br>
<UL>In R<SUB>2 </SUB>above 1R<SUB>2</SUB>2 and 2R<SUB>2</SUB>1,  but 1 <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#185;</FONT>
 2 hence not anti symmetric</UL>


<B><P>Transitive Relations</P>
</B>
<P>A relation R on a set A is <B>transitive </b>if <B>whenever aRb and bRc then aRc</B>.</P>
<P>i.e. <B>(a,b), (b,c) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R then (a,c) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R.</P></B>

<B><P>Examples:</B>Consider the set A = {1, 2, 3, 4}

<br><LI><b>R<SUB>1</SUB> = {(1,1), (1,2), (2,3), (1,3), (4,4)} </b>

<P>1R<SUB>1</SUB>2, 2R<SUB>1</SUB>3, require 1R<SUB>1</SUB>3 and (1,3) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 R<SUB>1</SUB>, so transitive.</P>

<LI><B>R<SUB>3</SUB> = {(1,3), (2,1)}</B>

<P>2R<SUB>3</SUB>1, 1R<SUB>3</SUB>3,  but (2,3) <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#207;</FONT>
 R<SUB>3</SUB>,  so not transitive.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Equivalence Relations</P>
</B>
<P>A relation R on a set S is an <b>equivalence</b> relation if R is<b>reflexive,  symmetric and transitive.</b>  i.e.</P>

<OL>

<LI>for every a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 S, aRa</LI>
<LI>if aRb then bRa</LI>
<LI>if aRb and bRc then aRc</LI></OL>

<br>

<P>Consider ‘=’ relation.</P>

<OL>

<LI>a = a  <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#34;</FONT>
 a <FONT FACE="Symbol">&#206;</FONT>
 S,</LI>
<LI>if a = b then b= a</LI>
<LI>if a=b, b=c, then a=c</LI></OL>
